result.execSummary:
The defendant Devin R Olson was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possession of THC (2nd+ Offense), a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(3g)(e).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

miscConds.notes:
Pay $250.00 fine plus costs.   Payment is due within 30 days.  If the Defendant cannot make the payment, he/she must report to the Clerk of Courts Office to set up a payment plan.  Failure to comply will result in other collection methods including a civil Judgment and/or suspension of your drivers license for two (2) years.  This judgment may be collected by income assignment if you fail to pay fines and costs as ordered.
------------------------------------

Pay DA service fees in the amount of $80.00.
------------------------------------

IT IS HEREBY ORDERED THAT the defendant's excess work release funds be applied to any & all outstanding Court obligations while serving his mandatory jail sentence.
------------------------------------

No alcohol.   No illegal drugs or drug paraphernalia.   Not to operate a motor vehicle without a valid driver's license. 
------------------------------------

IT IS ORDERED, pursuant to Wis. Stats. Sec. 973.015, that upon successful completion of the sentence imposed WITH NO VIOLATION OF THE RULES OF PROBATION and NO EARLY TERMINATION OF PROBATION,  the Clerk of Court shall issue an order expunging the record.
------------------------------------

Counseling as recommended by Probation Agent.   Provide biological specimen to state crime lab for DNA analysis, and pay DNA analysis surcharge.   The defendant must pay Department of Corrections Supervision fees.
------------------------------------

AODA assessment and follow through with recommendations.
------------------------------------
Pay Sheriff fees in the amount of $41.85.

3:02 p.m.  Court in session.  Case called.  Appearances given.  
Haley Jo Johnson appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  
Defendant Devin R Olson in court with attorney Rebecca Hammock.  
Matter is before the Court for plea and sentencing.  
Attorney Hammock recites the terms of the agreement.  

Defendant to plead to Count #1.  
Count #2 is to be dismissed and read-in.  
Withheld sentence - 2 years probation.  
Conditions of probation:  
Thirty (30) days in Jail with work release - to commence on or before 02/29/2016  
$250.00 Fine plus court costs  
Submit DNA sample and pay surcharge  
AODA assessment and follow through with recommendations  
Counseling as recommended by Agent  
No weapons  
No alcohol  
No drugs or drug paraphernalia  
No driving without a valid license  

Parties are free to argue expungement.  

Court has plea colloquy with the Defendant. 
Defendant enters a GUILTY plea to Count #1 of the Information.  
Defendant acknowledges prior conviction.  
Court finds plea to have been entered knowingly, voluntarily and intelligently.  
Statement by Defendant.  
Court will adopt the sentence recommendation of the parties.  

Argument by Attorney Rea as to expungement.  
Argument by Attorney Hammock as to expungement.  
Statement by Defendant.  
3:15 p.m.  Court proceeds with making its record.  
Court believes the defendant needs one more chance.  
Court finds expunction would benefit the Defendant and society would not be harmed.  
Court further orders that there be no violation of the rules of probation and no early termination of probation to qualify for expungement.  

Attorneys agree defendant is entitled to four (4) days dead time if probation is revoked.  
The cash bail will be applied to the fine and court costs.  Defendant is to set up a payment plan for any remaining balance.  
Defendant advised by Court that he is to immediately report to Jail to submit a DNA sample.  
3:19 p.m.  Court in recess.
